            content: "We are raised to believe that family is strictly defined by bloodlines, genetic trees, and shared last names. But as we navigate the rough oceans of adulthood, we quickly learn that true family extends far beyond the confines of biology. Family is defined by the people in your life who fiercely want you in theirs; the ones who choose you, day after day, not out of obligation, but out of genuine love.\n\nIt's the unconditional, often silent support they offer when the rest of the world turns its back and the lights go out. These are the people who see you at your absolute worst—stripped of your accomplishments, broken in spirit—and still look at you like you are a masterpiece. We argue with them, we fight stubbornly over trivial things, we distance ourselves when pride takes over, but the underlying foundation remains unshaken.\n\n<span class=\"highlight\">At the end of a long, bruising day, true family is the quiet, dimly lit harbor waiting patiently for your restless ship to return.</span> They don't demand explanations for the scars you gathered out at sea; they just help you toss the anchor, wrap a warm blanket around your tired shoulders, and tell you that you are finally home.",
            fact: "Oxytocin, often dubbed the 'cuddle hormone' or 'bonding hormone', is heavily released during physical contact and deep conversations with loved ones, solidifying emotional trust."
