            title: "The Inheritance of Wounds",
            content: "We look at our parents through the unforgiving lens of their failures, compiling silent lists of all the things they did wrong and all the ways they fell short of the idealized figures we needed them to be. But what we rarely acknowledge is that they were navigating the exact same labyrinth of life without a map, using only the broken compass handed down by their own flawed parents.\n\nTrauma travels through family lines until someone is ready to feel it. The anger your father couldn't express became the shouting you endured; the grief your mother suppressed became the emotional distance you felt. We inherit their unhealed wounds long before we inherit their physical traits. Forgiveness doesn't mean excusing the damage they caused, but it does require the sobering realization that they were likely bleeding onto you from cuts they didn't even know they had.\n\n<span class=\"highlight\">You are not just a child of your parents; you are the unwitting collision of generations of unresolved pain, and it is entirely up to you whether you pass that heavy baton forward, or finally snap it in half.</span> Breaking a generational curse isn't glorious; it looks like sitting alone on a Tuesday, choosing to respond with patience instead of the rage that feels native to your blood.",
